The offices include a kindergarten, architects understood
The Avriopoint administration building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would expect to hide a mini-school with everything that belongs to it - with colorful walls, imaginative furniture, a bunch of toys and even a miniature playground on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design employees can visit it.
Arch.Design, a project-architectonic company, whose studios produced a number of important Brno buildings, has been counting on space for its corporate minischool since the first drawings of the Avriopoint building.
She employs almost 90 people, mostly at the age of babyboom, and she cared that women designers and architects could quickly return to work.
Along with the possibility of abbreviated work, the kindergarten is a benefit that Arch.Design offers to its employees within the social program.
Builders and architects thus have the opportunity to combine demanding jobs with child care.
The employees of Arch.Design themselves invented the mini-school and managed to obtain a subsidy from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs with the support of the management.
The company mini-school is financed by the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment and the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to grant financing (subsidisation of CZK 2, 8 million), they were able to purchase equipment and equipment and provide qualified staff and operation for two years.
After the financial subsidy has been exhausted (2 years), Arch.Design is obliged to operate a mini-school at its own expense for 3 years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and the application for the subsidy was significantly supported by Economy Rating.
The care is provided by qualified staff, all-day care is provided by a nurse and a school teacher, so children can go to kindergarten without an age limit, yet most of them are over 3 years old.
Because it is a "minimum school", only 5 children can be present at the same time, but during the day more can be replaced.
The operation of the kindergarten is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the kindergarten regardless of the hierarchy of the position in the company.
Although it is individual education and care, the programme content in the mini-school is comparable to the framework programme of pre-school education.
Children not only play here, but they are also provided with quality teaching - from basic recognition to preparation to school benches, the English language is also taught.
The class is equipped not only with toys, stimulating games, but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of young children directly in the company creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check on their children at any time, and stress situations with delayed picking up children from preschools away from their parents ’ workplace are falling apart.
Parents use their working hours more productively.
No wonder there is a naturally loyal employee-employer relationship.
Arch.Design has thus joined Czech companies, which offer a significant benefit in recruiting new employees, are friendly to the family and through this program strengthened personnel marketing.
The house of bones fascinates after 100 years. Check the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the staircase resembles the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are open fish mouth.
This is the Casa Batlló house in Barcelona by Catalan architect Antoni Gaudi.
Thanks to its organic shapes, the house earned the nickname House of Bones from the locals.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, tile fragments and mosaics, facade reminiscent of scales and ubiquitous soft curves are all typical of Antoni Gaudi's Art Nouveau.
The front of the house is played by dream lines, tender colors and textures resembling nature and animals.
The detailed observation shows geometry, rhythm and precisely thought-out order.
At night, the whole facade of houses sounds even more dramatic, lit so that the impression of the gloss of colors is enhanced.
The winding and twisting of shapes appear equally in the interiors.
Wood in waves copies window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, eyes and rails.
The Batlló house, which stands in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43, was rebuilt in 1877 by the architect Emilio Sal Cortes.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, rich industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on tearing down the old building and building a completely new one, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea for an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
The apartment house Casa Batlló was not designed by Antoni Gaudi himself.
Architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It was on his design board that decorations were created for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the use of mosaics on the facade.
Many other creators and artists also worked on the facade.
The joint work on Casa Batlló's designs started with successful cooperation between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudí's house Casa Milá and the park Güell, in which other Gaudí's works are.
Soon after the completion of the house, the locals earned the nickname "House of Bones" thanks to their organic shapes.
Others began to call it a "singing house" because of a specific window opening mechanism.
It is also said that the sword of St. George, patron of Catalonia, is shaped at the top of the building.
Hidden religious motifs include other sculptural elements of the building.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system with ventilation vents and typical chimneys for his time.
Bizarre may seem to be their 45 - degree inclination.
In the creation of Gaudí he did not completely respect the construction regulations of that time and did not allow them to bind him.
At the beginning of the construction, he obtained a building permit from the city, but the figures on the planned reconstruction were so vague that two years later, when finishing, the city council was destroyed and asked for correction.
For example, the council objected to the fact that the building also interfered with the pillar and the public sidewalk.
On the contrary, only 15 days after the challenge of the city district, Josep Batlló requested (and successfully obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself moved to lower floors.
The gallery on the second floor was a social parlour and on the third floor was a bedroom and private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The whole six-story house crosses the staircase, which can be reached up to the roof terrace itself.
The essential elements of the reconstruction were the abolition of all right angles and straight lines and their replacement with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept of connecting spaces.
The social part can be fully connected by opening the salon doors and the larger society can communicate comfortably without maintaining the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
Apart from the new façade, Gaudí's house also acquired unusual roofing and two additional floors.
Gaudí's game with light, blue and white glazed tiles, with which the interior yard is covered, and skylights is also impressive.
The game of two colors adds maximum light on all floors of the house.
Simply bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which absorbs the sun’s rays.
Casa Batlló, which was placed in the Unesco World Heritage Fund in 2005, can be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and luxurious apartment made available to the public.
The owners chose this step only in 2002, on the occasion of celebrating the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They remained on the tours because they found it to be a very advantageous business and, moreover, extended the tours to common and attic spaces, including the roof terrace.
Admission to the monument is definitely not negligible, it is EUR 16.50 and students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards have a 20% discount.
The sum considerably exceeds the price of admission to other Gaudi buildings in the city.
If you want to taste the real atmosphere of the house with dragon towers, you must quickly become friends with one of the residents and visit it directly at home.
