People watching machines want more and more parents, so they want to keep their children safe.
Fearing for their own child brings more and more people to the idea of GPS surveillance.
The system originally designed for the search for cars can also monitor the movement of people, and thus help in cases such as the disappearance of 9-year-old Anička Janatková.
So far, the device is about the size of a matchbox, but soon it can only be as big as a watch.
A number of people got scared of the missing Anička case and started looking for means to protect their children better.
Even at the cost of violating their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that it is not spying, but another means of reducing the likelihood of a tragedy happening," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, who is one of the suppliers of surveillance equipment on the Czech market.
"I admit that in a certain case such devices may be misused, for example, if they are put in a bag to someone who does not know about it, but we have not yet encountered such a case."
"Most of the customers actually buy it for security reasons," Pilin added.
According to him, the child should always know what the box is for and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child doesn't want to wear something like this, they'll just get rid of it.
"Even very young children show great creativity in how to deliberately lose things when they don't want to be controlled."
"In the past, large expectations were triggered by mobile phones in parents, but they can be turned off just like these tracking devices," Bočková says.
According to her, it is also questionable whether such equipment would actually help in the event of an attack.
"As far as the kidnapping is concerned, the perpetrator practically always ensures that the child has no electronics on him that might reveal his location."
"Now it's a phone."
"When the tracking devices begin to expand, they will be looking for them, because their sale will certainly be supported by massive advertising."
"In that case, criminals will always be one step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, it admits that a similar device may help in the event of sudden pedophile attacks.
According to Robert Čech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services both for cars and for persons, even if immediate destruction of the tracking device occurs after the attack, his presence can help.
"The device can be set for regular positioning after a certain period of time."
"If it is damaged, at least the last position of the person concerned will be available."
"Dearer devices have built-in tiltometers, so even if one slips and stays still, the machine immediately sends a warning with a positioning," she says.
According to him, a similar service can be carried out by smart mobile phones with navigation, where you can upload special software.
The problem with current surveillance units is that they are either devices similar to matchbox size pendants or smaller mobile phones.
It's always the risk of losing them.
According to Pilin of Macro Weil, this is why the device now looks like a normal digital watch.
"It will have the greatest advantage that a possible aggressor may not recognize a tracking device at all."
"Or he won't recognize them until after a while and that can give the police extra time," he adds.
Whether they develop tracking devices into bracelets or pendants, they will still use the same technology that is used to watch cars.
This is a combination of GPS tracking (which uses common autonavigation) and mobile phone functions that report the current position of the car.
