The United States amends the rules for issuing visas
People will have to contact the Service Centres before they interview the Consular Department; the costs will be lower and the waiting time will be reduced.
As of 10 January 2011, the visa negotiation process at the United States Embassy and consulates will change.
with the new procedure, most applicants will have to contact the Service Centres for Visa Applicants (abbreviated from ASC English) before interviewing the Consular Department.
The staff from the ASC will collect biometric information from the applicant and these will be evaluated by the Consular Department before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, no longer need to pay the fee for arranging the meeting, the second for processing the application and more for delivering the document by the transport service.
The applicant shall pay only one fee covering all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: an amount equivalent to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for a visa application (including temporary worker visas) and $390 for a visa for traders and investors.
People who wish to renew their visa will not have to interview a consular officer, but will only turn to the nearest ASC, where they will submit their documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
Since biometric information will be collected in the ASC, applicants who will require a second meeting with an interview at the Consular Department will spend less time here than in the past.
Likewise, those who apply for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra $26 service fee.
For further information on the new visa application process, please visit the following website http://mexico.usembassy.gov/bolitines/sp101201_Visa-FAQs.html
