The discovery will be presented tomorrow at 1 p.m. by experts in astrobiology, science that deals with the study of origin, evolution, dissemination and future of life in space, at a press conference at NASA headquarters in Washington.
When she invited journalists, NASA assured itself that she would present "a discovery that would cause a breakthrough in the search for extraterrestrial life", arousing speculation by experts from other countries.
The discovery could confirm the theory that there are other creatures besides us, living in inhospitable conditions that have been considered uninhabitable, and who could represent the possibility of becoming intelligent creatures, such as humans, if the conditions in which they live improve.
It appears to be a microbe found at the bottom of Lake Mono in the Yosemist National Park in California, where it lives in an environment that was considered too toxic for any form of life, since the lake is rich in arsenic.
The creature somehow uses arsenic for its life, and it is this ability that increases the likelihood that similar life could exist on other planets that do not have the atmosphere as it is on Earth.
According to astrobiologists, if these organisms use arsenic in their metabolism, it will be proven that "there is another, another life form different from the one we know".
The space agency will announce the true reach of discovery at tomorrow's press conference.
The conference will be attended by geobiologist Pamela Conrad, who studies the possibility of life on Mars; biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists who examine Titan (the largest month of Saturn) with the prospect that its chemical composition is similar to that on Earth.
