Climate: how France hacked its promises of funding
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to test compliance with promises for quickly unblocked financing (fast start or premature) implemented by developed countries.
And the big French hacks have been exposed
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion in 2010-2012.
The European Union has promised €7.2 billion for three years and France €1.26 billion (that is, €420 million a year).
At the start of COP16, the EU drew a big ace to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start funding: a report detailing the action of its Member States, press conference, grand side event, distribution of brochures...
A transparent operation priceless and valued at its true value: developed countries and civil society would want all developed countries and civil society to do them the same and with the same degree of accuracy.
The EU announces that it released EUR 2.2 billion in 2010, bringing it on the right track to keep its promise of 7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we focus on the detail, we find that things are much more complicated.
Under the Copenhagen Agreement, these funds are 'new and additional' to ensure that the increased burden is realised without harming the development aid.
Unfortunately, there's no match for what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission has proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 as a reference: international funding has been preserved and it adds 150 million to it for three years of the title of fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment dates or with dates at the level of public development assistance.
On the other hand, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous periods or to the global level of Public aid for the development of d'Aide publique au développement.
Specifically, the overall amount of support from France to developing countries may remain constant (or even decrease) to comply with its commitment to the financing of "new and additional"...
Another crucial element is the distribution of donations and loans.
There is not yet a rule and everyone chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that €1 borrowed is equal to €1 donated.
Clearly, it is hard to prove: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be demonstrated for some investments that are profitable (often projects linked to the reduction of emissions, consisting of more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro that we receive as the equivalent of one euro that we give ... , we should not see it as the value of the loan to the creditor country (i.e. the interest rate equivalent).
But France can only provide such a justification: 'respects' its commitment of EUR 420 million, making it 91.5% loan (EUR 389.8 million) and 8.5% donations (EUR 36.1 million) - see the EU document so that you can verify it for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union that makes use of the loan on such a scale.
Germany requested 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) complied with their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union spends €1 on satisfying its promise, France only gives 10 centimes and considers this effort to be comparable.
That's a beautiful conjurer's piece!
To summarise, when financing a fast start, France operates with double fraud: on the one hand, with the development of the share over time and on the other hand, with a real financial burden.
Although it only spends EUR 36.1 million, it can convince itself that it issues EUR 420 million "new and additional" in connection with its promises.
The manipulation of the Minister of Finance (because it seems that although it is Bercy who has made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, at the same time within the EU (why would the Member States continue to donate when all they need to do is lend?) and when negotiating, because developing countries are not completely naive...
The early funding chapter is just a small question, relatively short-term, in relation to the series of climate discussions.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope this isn't our case.
Whatever it is, it is necessary to draw on the knowledge from this first year of early funding.
First, France should announce the change in its way of keeping accounting records for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its obligations and decency and fairness towards other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France should avoid discussing long-term funding contributions (another fundamental chapter currently discussed): we will not escape the question of 'additionality' or the way in which loans are recorded.
France should change its position to become as progressive on these deposits as it is with others.
So everyone is putting hope into the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Koscius-Morizet, who will be arriving in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement about France's fast start and its vision of 'additionality' and the use of loans could lead to an increase in the level of international confidence necessary to move forward in discussions.
